      model_name: "gemini-flash-latest"
      thinking_level: 3
    }
    started_at {
      seconds: 1782757611
      nanos: 913425402
    }
  }
  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining Notification Service Goals**\n\nOkay, I\'ve started defining the core components for the push notification system. I\'m focusing on the service that manages subscriptions, persisting them locally. The goal is to make it able to trigger native notifications and, importantly, simulate screen notifications. I\'m considering the best data structures for persistent local storage of subscription data. I need to make it able to trigger native notifications as well.\n\n\n**Developing Notification Service**\n\nI\'m now creating `src/utils/pushNotificationService.ts`. I\'m using the native HTML5 `Notification` API. I\'ve discovered the `Notification.requestPermission()` promise and I\'m figuring out how to construct notifications with title, body, and icon. I\'m also considering potential iframe restrictions and how to handle errors gracefully when the user declines or blocks notifications. I\'m thinking about making sure that the service still functions, even if native notifications are unavailable.\n\n\n**Designing Simulated Device Notifications**\n\nNow I\'m designing the simulated in-app device notification. I envision a visually striking overlay at the top of the viewport. This will be an exact replica of an iOS/Android push notification, complete with the CementMaster PTW icon, title, subtitle, and action buttons. I\'m focusing on creating an audio cue with the Web Audio API to generate a subtle beep. This requires no external dependencies!\n\n\n**Implementing Notification Triggers**\n\nI\'m now integrating an event emitter system within `/src/utils/pushNotificationService.ts` to trigger notifications globally. This will allow any component to signal a notification, which the root App layout or `NotificationOverlay` can then display as a banner. I\'m focusing on permission management, including `isSupported()`, `getPermissionStatus()`, `requestPermission()`, and `subscribe(empCode: string)` methods. I am storing subscriber records in `localStorage` mapping employee code.\n\n\n**Refining Notification Structure**\n\nI am now focusing on the structure of the push notification system and how notifications are sent. I\'m exploring the `sendNotification` function, which handles both native and simulated notifications. This involves checking for permission, dispatching an event to render a React UI banner and logging the notifications in `localStorage` for historical review. I need to figure out where to place the TypeScript type declarations for this. I\'m considering adding the types in the `pushNotificationService.ts` file versus a `src/types.ts` edit to add `PushNotificationLog` and update any states we need.\n\n\n**Defining Notification Types**\n\nI\'ve decided to formalize the TypeScript types for the notification system. I\'m leaning towards defining `PushNotificationLog` and related types within `src/types.ts`. I think this enhances code organization and maintainability. This is better than declaring them in the service file. I will look at that now. I\'m now looking at a clean implementation of the `/src/utils/pushNotificationService.ts`. I\'m figuring out how to generate a synthetic notification sound using the Web Audio API. I am aiming to generate a double beep sound with it.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create a comprehensive push notification utility in `/src/utils/pushNotificationService.ts`. This service will leverage the native HTML5 **Notification API** for real operating system push alerts, feature a **Web Audio API** synthetic double-beep sound, manage subscriptions, maintain local history logs, and use a lightweight Pub/Sub event emitter to trigger real-time, interactive slide-down overlays in the UI."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 10
      nanos: 275881606
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
